<br>
Set-Up 1: Intetelligence as key stat:<br>
I use this when I'm fighting unmezzable mobs in a group which I don't intend to charm. I focus on INT as the primary stat. I also use this when I'm soloing with summoned pet in which I am casting mainly buffs, debuffs, DoT, nuke and rune to preserve my pet's life as it melees and keeps the darn thing off me. In this scenerio, mana pool rules and optimizing it is my goal.<br>
<br>
Set-Up 2: Charisma as key stat:<br>
I use this when either grouped in a situation where I am responsible for crowd control or I'm playing with charmed mobs. I don't, however, neglect INT, most of my permanent items (that I always wear) have both, but with INT and CHA buffs, CHA comes out a little ahead. You still want to have a good mana pool to work from, but eventhough CHA's effect on mez/charm is debated, I've found that it can make a big difference and if you happen to be fighting a mob that charms, you will be more protected from it effecting you. This is also an excellent setup for purchasing spells, jewelery crafting components, and any other vendor shopping purchases you intend to make. (CHA at 120 will give you the minimum price for a vendor sold item, any more than that won't effect cost)<br>
<br>
Set-Up 3: Resist Gear<br>
This will be something to worry about at a later time, but worth mentioning now. I use a resist gear set-up when fighting in high level dungeons, usually with guild. In this set-up, getting your resists up is important for that is what will keep you alive when a mob is AoE-ing the room and you have to be in the line of fire. You probably won't be doing any mezzing or charming since the mobs will likely be too high for your spells to effect or simply unmezzable. Mana is still important, but there will be another enchanter to help split up duties and your primary job will consist of keeping the casters minds' clear, keeping the tanks swinging swiftly, Tashing the mob, and often man tapping/sieving the casting mobs so they don't cast complete heal or gate. The clerics will have the tanks' health as top priority, so doing your part in having your resists as high as you can to save them from having to heal you helps to keep the momentum of the raid moving smoothly.<br>
<br>
<br>
My advise, start a collection of both INT and CHA gear and find the combination that suits your fighting style, location, and effectiveness. Every stat has it's importance in different situations. Yes, HP and AC are important, dexterity helps you cast (especially against interruptions from mobs), agility helps you dodge mobs hitting you and determines AC, stamina allots more HP to your overall pool, strength lets you carry more gear and loot. The only stat you shouldn't worry about is wisdom, it has no importance to you as an INT caster.<br>
<br>
 <p>-Enraptura Failsafe 
